eo games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1994 In video games}}\n[[Category:1994 in video games| ]]\n[[Category:Video games by year]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2009}}\n{{Year nav topic5|1994|video games}}\n\n1994 has seen many sequels and prequels in video games and several new titles such as ''[[Super Metroid]]'', ''[[Donkey Kong Country]]'' and ''[[Sonic & Knuckles]]''.\n\n==Events==\n*[[Nintendo]] proclaims \"1994: The Year of the Cartridge\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/'SHOWTIME'+AT+THE+NINTENDO+BOOTH+FOR+THE+WINTER+CONSUMER+ELECTRONICS...-a014671344|title=Showtime at the Nintendo Booth for the Winter Consumer Electronics Show|publisher=Free Library|date=January 5, 1994|accessdate=February 10, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Nintendo Australia]] Pty. Ltd, the Australian subsidiary of [[Nintendo]] Co., Ltd is established and opened by [[Hiroshi Yamauchi]] and effectively ends [[Mattel]] Australia's distribution of Nintendo's products throughout Australia.\n*\"Project Reality\" is renamed the Nintendo Ultra 64. The console's design is revealed to the public for the first time in spring 1994.\n*April \u2013 Interactive Digital Software Association (IDSA) founded (name changed to the [[Entertainment Software Association]] in 2003); IDSA founds [[Entertainment Software Rating Board]] (ESRB)\n*April 28 \u2013 [[Sega]] and [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]] make a venture to create video games, movies, and television programs.\n*June 24 \u2013 The [[Computer Game Developers Association]] is formed by Ernest W. Adams.\n*November \u2013 ''Game Zero'' magazine drops their print format and becomes the first video game news magazine on the web.\n*November 10 \u2013 [[William Higinbotham]], creator of ''[[Tennis for Two]]'' (1958), dies at 84.\n\n===Notable releases===\n*January \u2013 ''[[Mega Man X]]'' is released in the US.\n*February 2 \u2013 ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog 3]]'' ([[Sega]], [[Sega Mega Drive|Mega Drive/Genesis]]), introduces [[Knuckles the Echidna]].\n*February 23 \u2013 ''[[Super Street Fighter II Turbo]]'' ([[Arcade games|Arcade]]), introduces [[Akuma (Street Fighter)|Akuma]].\n*March 15 \u2013 ''[[Mega Man 6]]'' is released in the US.\n*March 19 \u2013 ''[[Super Metroid]]'' ([[SNES]]), distributed on a 24-[[megabit]] cartridge. Super Metroid was called the \"best game of all time\" by ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'' in 2002.\n*March 25 \u2013 [[Bethesda Softworks|Bethesda]] releases [[The Elder Scrolls: Arena]]\n*March 27 \u2013 [[Origin Systems|Origin]] releases ''[[Wing Commander III: Heart of the Tiger]]'', based both around space simulation gameplay and an interactive movie with big-name actors. It's one of the most expensive games developed, with a budget of US$4 million.\n*April 2 \u2013 [[Square (video game company)|Square Co.]] releases ''[[Final Fantasy VI]]'' (then known as ''Final Fantasy III'' in North America) for the SNES on April 2 in [[Japan]] and October 11 in [[North America]].\n*April 3 \u2013 [[Accolade (company)|Accolade]] releases Bubsy II on GameBoy, Sega Genesis, and SNES.\n*May 3 \u2013 [[Epic MegaGames]] releases ''[[Jazz Jackrabbit (1994 video game)|Jazz Jackrabbit]]'', a console-style \"animal with attitude\" platformer.\n*June 2 \u2013 [[Sir-Tech]] releases [[turn-based tactics]] game ''[[Jagged Alliance]]'', the first installment of ''[[Jagged Alliance (series)|Jagged Alliance]]'' series.\n*June 14 \u2013 [[Nintendo]] releases [[Donkey Kong 94]] for the Game Boy. It featured remakes of the first four stages of the original game plus adding 96 [[puzzle]] based levels. Mario is much more versatile in this version, as he can backflip, handstand, and spin on wires. It received critical acclaim and became a Game Boy fan favorite and classic.\n*July \u2013 [[LucasArts]] releases ''[[Star Wars: TIE Fighter|TIE Fighter]]''.\n*July 5 \u2013 [[Capcom]] releases ''[[Darkstalkers]]''.\n*July 15 \u2013 [[Acclaim Entertainment]] and [[Mirage Technologies (Multimedia) Ltd.|Mirage]] releases the fighting game ''[[Rise of the Robots]]''.\n*August 2 \u2013 [[Shiny Entertainment]] releases ''[[Earthworm Jim (video game)|Earthworm Jim]]''.\n*August 25 \u2013 [[SNK Playmore]] releases ''[[The King of Fighters]]''.\n*August 27 \u2013 [[Nintendo]] releases [[EarthBound|Mother 2]] for the Super Famicom in Japan, which was released almost a year later in North America on the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System]] as ''EarthBound''. ''EarthBound'' also introduces [[Ness (character)|Ness]].\n*August 31 \u2013 [[Electronic Arts]] releases ''[[The Need for Speed]]'' for the [[3DO Interactive Multiplayer|3DO]], which begins the [[List of best-selling video game franchises|most successful]] [[Need For Speed (series)|racing game franchise]] of all time.\n*September \u2013 [[MicroProse]] releases ''[[Master of Magic]]''.\n*September 9 \u2013 The Super NES version of ''[[Mortal Kombat 2]]'' is released with all blood and fatalities left intact, the first major release on any Nintendo console at that point to have such content.\n*September 22 \u2013 [[Origin Systems]] releases [[Looking Glass Studios]]' ''[[System Shock]]''.\n*October 10 \u2013 [[id Software]] releases ''[[Doom II]]'' and [[Dave D. Taylor]] creates a [[Linux]] port of the original ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'', becoming the first major game for the new operating system.\n*October 17<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/genesis/586468-sonic-and-knuckles/data |title=Sonic & Knuckles Release Information for Genesis |website=GameFAQs |date=October 17, 1994 |accessdate=November 5, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121031063014/http://www.gamefaqs.com/genesis/586468-sonic-and-knuckles/data |archivedate=October 31, 2012 }}</ref> \u2013 ''[[Sonic & Knuckles]]'' is released. It allows a player to connect previous Sonic games to the cartridge, making [[Knuckles the Echidna|Knuckles]] playable in them.\n*October 25 \u2013 [[MicroProse]] releases ''[[UFO: Enemy Unknown]]'' and the Strategy Game of the Year ''[[Master of Orion]]''.\n*October 28 \u2013 ''[[Killer Instinct (1994 video game)|Killer Instinct]]'' ([[Rare (company)|Rare]]), the first arcade machine with an internal [[hard disk]].\n*October 28 \u2013 [[Accolade]]'s [[Bubsy II]] is released for Sega Genesis and Super NES.\n*November 21 \u2013 Sega releases the 32X add-on in the US alongside ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'' and ''Star Wars Arcade''.\n*November 21 \u2013 [[Nintendo]] releases [[Rare (company)|Rare]]'s ''[[Donkey Kong Country]]'' ([[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]]), featuring 3D pre-rendered graphics. It also introduces [[Diddy Kong]] and [[King K. Rool]].\n*November 23 \u2013 [[Blizzard Entertainment]] releases the [[real-time strategy]] game ''[[Warcraft: Orcs & Humans|Warcraft]]'', which spawns a franchise and influences many later games.\n*November 23 \u2013 [[Sierra On-Line]] releases the computer adventure game [[King's Quest VII: The Princeless Bride]], the first in the series to use \"SVGA\" graphics.\n*December 9 \u2013 [[Namco]] releases its first 3D fighting game ''[[Tekken (video game)|Tekken]]'' to arcades.\n*December 10 \u2013 [[Nintendo]] releases ''[[Wario's Woods]]'', the last official game to be released on the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] (NES) in North America before Nintendo would officially discontinue production of the console.\n*December 16 \u2013 ''[[Mega Man X2]]'' is released in Japan.\n*December 21 \u2013 [[Bungie]] releases ''[[Marathon (computer game)|Marathon]]'', one of the earliest original (non-ported) [[first-person shooter]]s for the [[Apple Macintosh|Macintosh]].\n*December 24 \u2013 ''[[Heretic (video game)|Heretic]]'' is released by id Software. It the first in [[Raven Software]]'s ''Heretic''/''Hexen'' series and also the first game bundled with [[DWANGO]], one of the earliest [[online multiplayer]] services\n*[[Maxis]] releases ''[[SimCity 2000]]'', sequel to the popular ''SimCity''.\n*[[Sega]] releases the ''[[Daytona USA (arcade game)|Daytona USA]]'' racing game in arcades.\n*[[Sensible Software]] releases ''[[Sensible Soccer (series)|Sensible World of Soccer]]'', regarded as the best [[Amiga]] game of all time by British Amiga magazine ''[[Amiga Power]]''.\n*[[Namco]] releases [[Point Blank (1994 video game)|Point Blank]] in arcades.\n\n===Hardware===\n*[[Aiwa]] releases the [[Variations of the Sega Mega Drive#Aiwa Mega-CD|Aiwa Mega-CD]] multimedia home console in Japan only.\n*[[Bandai]] releases the [[Playdia]] multimedia home console.\n*[[Nippon Electric Corporation|NEC]] releases the [[PC-FX]] multimedia home console.\n*[[Sega]]:\n**introduces the North American cable TV [[Sega Channel]] in cooperation with Time Warner ([[AOL Time Warner]]); the subscription service provides [[Sega Genesis]] games via cable box to customers\n**releases the [[Sega 32X]] add-on for the [[Sega Mega Drive|Sega Mega Drive/Genesis]] in [[Europe]] (November 14), [[North America]] (November 21) and [[Japan]] (December 3)\n**releases the [[Sega Nomad]] handheld console in [[North America]], a portable [[Sega Genesis]].\n**releases the [[Sega Saturn]] home console in [[Japan]] on November 22\n*[[SNK Playmore|SNK]] releases the [[Neo Geo CD]] home console.\n[[File:PSX-Console-wController.png|250px|thumb|right|PlayStation video game console, first released in Japan]]\n*[[Sony]] releases the [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] home console in Japan on December 3.\n*[[Nintendo]] releases the [[Super Game Boy]] adapter for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]] home console.\n*[[Atari Corporation]] discontinues the [[Atari Lynx|Lynx]] handheld system.\n\n===Business===\n*New companies: [[Neversoft]]\n*Defunct: [[Commodore International|Commodore]], [[Tradewest]]\n*September 14 \u2013 Video gaming magazine ''[[Nintendomagasinet]]'' is cancelled after four years. Number 9 of 1994 would have been released on this day, but instead the magazine joins ''[[Super PLAY|Super Power]]''.\n*[[3D Realms|Apogee]] establishes the 3D Realms Entertainment division.\n*[[Blizzard Entertainment]] is renamed from Silicon & Synapse.\n*[[Strategic Simulations|SSI]] sold to [[Mindscape]]\n*[[Alpex]] Computer Corp. v. Nintendo lawsuit: Alpex sues Nintendo over patent infringements related to the NES. Nintendo loses the case. (In 1996 this ruling was reversed by an appeals court, which determined that no patents had been infringed upon.)<ref>{{cite magazine |last=|first= |title=Tidbits...|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=90|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=January 1997|page=28}}</ref>\n**Nintendo of America, Inc. v. [[Dragon Pacific]] Intern\n\n==Sales==\n===Highest-selling console and handheld titles according to Babbage's===\n[[GameStop|Babbage's]], an American video game retailer, released an ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]''-exclusive monthly list of the chain's highest-selling console and handheld titles.<ref name=\"EGMMar1994\">{{cite magazine |url=https://retrocdn.net/images/a/ae/EGM_US_056.pdf |title=EGM Hot Top Tens |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |date=March 1994 |pages=48}}</ref><ref name=\"EGMApr1994\">{{cite magazine |url=https://retrocdn.net/images/e/ed/EGM_US_057.pdf |title=EGM Hot Top Tens |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |date=April 1994 |pages=52}}</ref><ref name=\"EGMMay1994\">{{cite magazine |url=https://retrocdn.net/images/9/92/EGM_US_058.pdf |title=EGM's Hot Top Tens |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |date=May 1994 |pages=46}}</ref><ref name=\"EGMJun1994\">{{cite magazine |url=https://retrocdn.net/images/8/8e/EGM_US_059.pdf |title=EGM's Hot Top Tens |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |date=June 1994 |pages=48}}</ref><ref name=\"EGMJul1994\">{{cite magazine |url=https://retrocdn.net/images/a/af/EGM_US_060.pdf |title=EGM's Hot Top Tens |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]] |date=July 1994 |pages=48}}</ref><ref name=\"EGMAug1994\">{{cite magazine |url=https://retrocdn.net/i